R Overview

  • R philosophy
    • Information is contained in objects (e.g.Â data, variables, models, plots)
    • Operations are represented by functions (e.g.Â sort data, fit model, plot results)
  • R comes with standard functions, but can expand functionality using packages (a.k.a. libraries)
    • Packages are bundles of reusable code (functions & data)
    • Must be downloaded once w/ install.packages() and loaded at start of R session w/ library()
install.packages("tidyverse")
library(tidyverse)
help(package = "tidyverse")

Functions

  • Functions create/modify objects according to arguments
    • E.g. Generate sequence from 3 to 5, increasing by .5
seq( from = 3, to = 5, by = .5)
## [1] 3.0 3.5 4.0 4.5 5.0

Input/Output

  • read_delim()/read_csv() reads tabular data (data frame) from spread-sheet like file (tab or comma delimited)
my_data = read_csv( file = 'C:/Users/sdamo/Documents/data.csv')
  • write_delim()/write_csv() writes tabular data (matrix or data frame) to such files
  • save()/load() writes/reads binary (non-readable) representation of R objects
    • When closing R, save.image() saves all objects in .RData file

Directories

  • Absolute file paths (e.g.Â C:/Users/nmoon/â€¦) are bad for reproducibility

  • Use relative file paths, relative to your working directory

    • To find/set working directory use getwd()/setwd()
    • Access working directory directly
getwd()
setwd("C:/Users/nmoon/...")
my_data = read_csv( file = 'data.csv')
  • R projects define working directory & help organize work
  • When you create an “R project” for your work, you wonâ€™t need to use setwd() because R will already know where to start looking for your files

Pipes

  • Pipe operator %>% passes object as functionâ€™s (first) argument x %>% f(y) = f(x, y) or y %>% f(x, .) = f(x, y)

  • Apply functions sequentially
    data %>% filter( ) %>% select( ) %>% summarize( )

  • Identical but much easier to read than
    summarize( select( filter(data) ) ) )

Data Visualization

  • Communicate information graphically through plots, charts, maps, etc.

  • High-level plot description based on layered grammar of graphics

    • Create plots by overlaying geometric objects on same coordinates

  • R package ggplot2 implements such grammar for creating plots in R

Graph Structure

  • Basic ingredients
    • Data
    • Aesthetic Mappings
    • Geometric Objects (lines, points, text, etc)
  • Extras
    • Statistics
    • Scales
    • Facets
    • Other adjustments (coordinates, annotations, positions)

Graph Structure

Aesthetic Mappings

  • Geometric objects convey information through their aesthetics (i.e.Â perceived characteristics)

  • Data variable(s) can be mapped to one or more aesthetics

  • Common aesthetic mappings

    • Location: x/y coordinates
    • Appearance: size, color, shape, etc

Gapminder Data

  • Gapminder Foundation is non-profit organization promoting world-wide social, economic and environmental development through the use of data and statistics
    • Excellent source of information about state of the world
  • gapminder package provides excerpt of available data
library(gapminder); glimpse(gapminder)

Plotting in ggplot2

  • Basic syntax ggplot( data, aes(...) ) + geom_*() + ...
gap07 <- gapminder %>% filter( year == "2007")
ggplot(gap07, aes(x = continent)) + geom_bar()

Scales

  • Scales control range of aesthetic mappings.

For example

ggplot(gap07, aes(x = continent, y = gdpPercap) ) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  scale_y_log10()

Faceting

Use facet_wrap() to create grid of sub-plots, one for each level of a variable.

In the example below, we use facet_wrap(facets = ~continent) to create a separate plot for each continent

ggplot(gap07, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap( facets = ~ continent)

Putting this all together

Suppose you wanted to create a visualization to illustrate the population growth in each continent since 1985.

The geom_point geometry produces a scatterplot - this is a good choice since weâ€™re interested in looking at the association between population (numerical) and year (numerical) across several groups (continents). The first step in creating an effective visualization is to think about the features you want.

  • x-axis variable and y-axis variable?
  • Are there groups within your data?
  • If there are different groups, how do you want to emphasize them? (e.g.Â different colours? a line for each group?)
  • Do you need to manipulate your dataframe to obtain the variables/groups listed above? (e.g.Â using filter, mutate, group_by, summarize,â€¦)

Putting this all together

gapminder %>% 
  filter(year > 1985) %>% 
  mutate(year=as.numeric(year), pop=as.numeric(pop)) %>% 
  group_by(year, continent) %>% 
  summarise(pop=sum(pop)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=pop, color=continent)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=year, y=pop, group=continent)) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(1987, 1992, 1997, 2002, 2007))
